    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-10-09T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-10-09T19:00:00-05:00" n="1009"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1009">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72111/4112a</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d1009fn1">The same, on the same date, to the
                        Chargé in France (No. 1770).</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1916-10-09T19:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 9, 1916, 7 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3909. German submarines active off coast: Apparent intention is to live up to
                    formal assurances given by Germany in regard to conduct of submarine warfare.
                    French Ambassador yesterday informally discussed question of modifying rules in
                    regard to all submarines entering, neutral ports. He was reminded of attitude of
                    Allies in refusing to consider any modification of rule applying to <pb
                        facs="1058" n="772" xml:id="pg_772"/> armed merchantmen in connection with
                    submarine warfare last spring on ground that no change could be made during
                    hostilities. Same point is being made in regard to British withdrawing blockade
                    ships from our coast in response to our protest. In case you should be asked to
                    discuss question it should be borne in mind that at that time the British ships
                    were stationed actually in mouth of Ambrose Channel in full sight of shore and
                    that this was causing unnecessary irritation. It should also be borne in mind
                    that British refused to admit our right to suggest that ships be withdrawn.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
